Great food and drinks.  The chef that opened this place used to work at Black Dog and was responsible for the success they had there, creating a lot of their dishes and techniques they still use. It was 1000x times better when he worked there. I guess he got bored of running the smoker all day and decided to start his own place doing chicken, he must've been tired of all that beef and pork. The result is a passion project from a chef that's been doing bbq for years and really knows what he's doing. There have been a lot of fun little experiments like pickled green tomatoes and green beans, but it's the classics like the fried chicken and pork belly that keep people coming back for a new take on old fashioned comfort food. They also have vege options, I like the tofu po' boy.

In short, if you can get in with no to little wait, enjoy! But if you show up and can't get a spot right away, save yourself some hassle and a ruined mood and go elsewhere.

We had just been to the Prairie Fruits Farm 100-Yard chef's dinner the night before, and this actually measured up as a great follow up. In town on a Friday night for a long work trip, I decided to check this place out for dinner.  Being alone means you eat at the bar, and being alone, married and pregnant can suck.  I was so happy to see a decent non-alchoholic drink offering... their "peacemaker" was phenomenal and perfect for a refreshing beverage on a hot night... and it gave me a fancy looking beverage while I ate at the bar  Bartender Anne was delightful, and quickly let me know to check the menu becuase things have changed (and based on some die-hard fan reviews apparently this place is very different now). Luckily I had no clue what I was getting into!!!  The bar had a great displayed selection of quality bottles, from my vantage point I could see an excellent variety of tequilas, and whiskeys and bourbons.  Bonus points for offering a popcorn tofu Pop Boy sandwhich and a side of Vegan potato salad... I'm a straying vegetarian while pregnant, but I love seeing quality options that are a true standing dish, and not just a menu item minus the meat.  Their fried chicken sandwhich was far better than I ever expected it to be. I haven't had that good of a fried chicken sandwhich since I lived down South in Georgia. A lovely chance for some proper fried chicken, while still being in the midwest.  Fries weren't hot or particularly great... But the sandwhich alone made this a 5 star experience. The really good drink helped, and it was nice having a bar tender who kept my water topped off on a hot day.

I’ve only been here during brunch so this rating is strictly on brunch service. Right when Watson’s first launched their brunch menu, I went with a friend. I had the chicken and waffles and a mimosa. The chicken was flavorful and had a slight heat to it. The waffle was crispy and sweet which made it a fantastic pairing to the chicken. The drink was reasonably priced and was a standard run of the mill mimosa.  Fast forward a year and some change. I visited Watson’s again with my friends as part of a birthday extravaganza. This time around, I had the country poutine and an alcoholic slushie. I cannot rave enough about the poutine. It came with cheese curds, sausage gravy, and a perfectly done chicken fried steak. This poutine was definitely large enough to share, but you’re not going to want to. Now what really knocked this meal out of the park was the tropical alcoholic slushie with flavors of mango and banana. It was smooth and sweet and you could barely taste the rum inside. Also, our waitress was completely knowledgeable on the whole menu and the drinks as well. This knowledgeable woman made our morning even better. I’ve fallen in love with Watson’s brunch from first bite, I hope you do too!
